Prerequisites
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 * clive >= 2.0.0  (http://clive.sourceforge.net)
 * Perl  >= 5.8    (http://perl.org)

If a module is listed as "opt." (optional), this means that the utility
works without it but some functionalities are disabled.

Most distros should have the modules listed below as installable packages.
If this is not the case, you can install the missing modules from CPAN
(http://cpan.org), e.g.:
    % cpan install WWW::Curl # as root or sudo

clivefeed
---------

* Config::Tiny/2.12           * WWW::Curl/4.05
* XML::RSS::LibXML/0.3002     * Clipboard/0.09 (opt.)
* Tk/804.027                  * URI::Escape/3.29
* Tk::DialogBox/4.013         * HTML::Strip/1.06
* Tk::FontDialog/0.15 (opt.)  * Tk::Tree/4.005

  * Clipboard       -- affects --paste
  * Tk::FontDialog  -- affects GUI font configuration

clivescan
---------

* Config::Tiny/2.12           * WWW::Curl/4.05
* Tk/804.027                  * Tk::Tree/4.005
* Tk::DialogBox/4.013         * Clipboard/0.09 (opt.)
* Tk::FontDialog/0.15 (opt.)  * HTML::TokeParser/2.37

  * Clipboard       -- affects --paste
  * Tk::FontDialog  -- affects GUI font configuration

clivepass
---------

* Crypt::PasswdMD5/1.3        * Crypt::Twofish2/1.01
* Crypt::Salt/0.01            * Config::Tiny/2.12


Installation
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Extract:
    % tar xvjf clive-utils-$release.tar.bz2
    % cd clive-utils-$release

Run:
    If the path to clive(1) utility is not specified (e.g. --clive=path), the
    clive-utils programs try to locate it in the $PATH.
        % clivefeed [option]... [URL]...
        % clivescan [option]... [URL]...
        % clivepass [option]...

    See also the configs/ for example configuration files. To minimize the
    overhead, it's a good idea to save the path to a configuration file.

Getting started:
    The manual pages are written in Perl Pod markup language and they are
    embedded in the script files. See "perldoc perlpod" for more info.
    You can access the manual page by using the --manual option, e.g.:
        % clivefeed --manual

    Or you can use the pod2(man|text|latex|html) utilities to convert the
    Pod to another format, e.g.:
        % pod2man clivefeed > clivefeed.1

    There is also the "genman" script which wraps the pod2man and produces
    the manual pages with the most common options. This script is used to
    generate the manual pages bundled with the source code.

See also:
    configs/ subdir for example configuration files


